@page "/learn/dpos"
@layout Consensus.Web.Components.Layout.MainLayout

<PageTitle>Delegated Proof of Stake · Tutorials · Consensus Lab</PageTitle>

<TutorialPage Title="Delegated Proof of Stake (DPoS)"
              Lede="Like a representative democracy for blockchains. Token holders vote for a small group of delegates who take turns adding blocks."
              Difficulty="Intermediate"
              ReadTime="~10 min">

    <h2>The basic idea</h2>

    <p>
        In Proof of Stake, anyone with enough coins can validate blocks directly. That's
        democratic, but it can be <em>slow</em> when thousands of validators have to coordinate.
        Delegated Proof of Stake solves that by adding a layer of indirection: instead of
        everyone validating, token holders <strong>vote</strong> for a small fixed-size committee
        — typically 21 to 101 delegates — who then take turns producing blocks in a strict
        rotation.
    </p>

    <p>
        Think of it like school council elections. The whole student body votes; the top few
        candidates take office; they make decisions for the year. If they do a bad job, next
        election they're voted out.
    </p>

    <div class="analogy">
        <strong>Analogy:</strong> If PoS is "everyone votes on every law", DPoS is "everyone
        votes for parliament, and parliament votes on the laws". Faster, but you have to trust
        the small group of representatives — and replace them if they misbehave.
    </div>

    <h2>How a round works, step by step</h2>

    <MermaidDiagram Caption="A DPoS round: elections + round-robin block production.">
flowchart TD
    Start([Election phase]) --> Vote[Token holders cast votes<br/>weighted by their balance]
    Vote --> Top[Top N candidates become<br/>active delegates]
    Top --> Schedule[Delegates are assigned<br/>a round-robin schedule]
    Schedule --> Slot[Each slot, the next<br/>delegate in line proposes a block]
    Slot --> Network[Other delegates verify<br/>and accept the block]
    Network --> NextSlot{More slots<br/>this term?}
    NextSlot -- Yes --> Slot
    NextSlot -- No --> Reelect[Re-run the election<br/>so unhappy voters can swap delegates]
    Reelect --> Start
    </MermaidDiagram>

    <h2>Watch a round play out</h2>

    <p>
        Seven delegates rotate around the protocol coordinator (centre). Once elected,
        each delegate takes turns producing a block in a strict order — slot 1 goes to
        Delegate 1, slot 2 to Delegate 2, and so on. Watch the gold highlight move around
        the ring as each delegate produces their block.
    </p>

    <ConsensusAnimation Title="Delegated PoS — round-robin block production"
                        Actors="@_dposActors" Steps="@_dposSteps" />

@code {
    private static readonly List<ConsensusAnimation.Actor> _dposActors =
        AnimationLayouts.RingWithCentre(
            peripheralCount: 7,
            centreId: "proto",
            centreLabel: "Protocol",
            centreColor: "#27ae60",
            centreIcon: "🗳",
            peripheralIdPrefix: "d",
            peripheralLabelPrefix: "Delegate",
            peripheralIcon: "👤");

    private static ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep SlotStep(int slot, string delegateId)
        => new(
            Title: $"Slot {slot}. {delegateId.ToUpper()} produces a block",
            Description: $"It's Delegate {slot}'s turn. They build and broadcast the next block to the network; the others verify in milliseconds.",
            Messages: AnimationLayouts.Broadcast(delegateId,
                Enumerable.Range(1, 7).Select(i => $"d{i}").Where(id => id != delegateId).ToList(),
                color: "#388e3c", label: "block").ToList(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> { delegateId });

    private static readonly List<ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep> _dposSteps = new()
    {
        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "Election. Token holders vote for delegates",
            Description: "Every token holder casts a stake-weighted vote. The top seven candidates become the active producers for this term. (Voting itself isn't shown — we start from the elected committee.)",
            Messages: AnimationLayouts.Broadcast("proto", Enumerable.Range(1, 7).Select(i => $"d{i}"),
                color: "#9b59b6", label: "elected").ToList(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"proto","d1","d2","d3","d4","d5","d6","d7"}),

        SlotStep(1, "d1"),
        SlotStep(2, "d2"),
        SlotStep(3, "d3"),
        SlotStep(4, "d4"),
        SlotStep(5, "d5"),
        SlotStep(6, "d6"),
        SlotStep(7, "d7"),

        new ConsensusAnimation.AnimationStep(
            Title: "End of term — re-election",
            Description: "Each term ends with another vote so unhappy token holders can swap out misbehaving delegates. A new committee takes over and the cycle repeats.",
            Messages: new List<ConsensusAnimation.Message>(),
            HighlightedActors: new HashSet<string> {"proto"}),
    };
}

    <h2>The election cycle</h2>

    <p>
        Two phases run continuously:
    </p>

    <ol>
        <li>
            <strong>Voting.</strong> Anyone holding tokens can vote for delegates. Votes are
            weighted by token balance — 1 token = 1 vote. Voters can change their vote any
            time; if a delegate starts misbehaving, voters can pull support from them within
            minutes.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Production.</strong> The top-ranked delegates rotate through fixed-length
            slots (often 0.5 to 3 seconds each). In each slot, exactly one delegate produces a
            block. The others verify it.
        </li>
    </ol>

    <p>
        Because slots are fixed and short, DPoS chains can finalize blocks <em>very</em> fast.
        EOS, for example, produces a new block every 500 milliseconds.
    </p>

    <h2>What happens if a delegate misbehaves?</h2>

    <p>
        Three layers of protection:
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li>
            <strong>Missed blocks are visible.</strong> Every delegate's track record (uptime,
            blocks produced vs missed) is public. A delegate who flakes out gets a bad
            reputation immediately.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Voters can swap them.</strong> Token holders can withdraw their vote
            instantly and shift it to a more reliable candidate. Bad delegates drop out of the
            top N and stop earning.
        </li>
        <li>
            <strong>Slashing.</strong> Many DPoS chains also penalize delegates who sign two
            blocks at the same height (a double-sign attack) by destroying their staked
            collateral.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>The real-world picture</h2>

    <p>
        DPoS was invented by Daniel Larimer for <strong>BitShares</strong> in 2014. The big
        examples since then:
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li><strong>EOS</strong> — 21 elected "Block Producers", 0.5-second slots</li>
        <li><strong>TRON</strong> — 27 "Super Representatives"</li>
        <li><strong>Steem</strong> — DPoS-powered social media platform</li>
        <li><strong>Cosmos</strong> — uses a hybrid PoS/DPoS approach via Tendermint</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Strengths and trade-offs</h2>

    <div class="pro-con-grid">
        <div class="pro-card">
            <h4>✅ Strengths</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>Very fast — sub-second block times</li>
                <li>High throughput — thousands of transactions per second</li>
                <li>Energy-efficient like PoS</li>
                <li>Bad actors can be voted out within minutes</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="con-card">
            <h4>⚠️ Trade-offs</h4>
            <ul>
                <li>More centralized — only N delegates produce blocks (often 21–101)</li>
                <li>Voter apathy: many token holders never vote</li>
                <li>Large token holders dominate elections</li>
                <li>"Cartel" risk: delegates can collude to share rewards</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Why the fairness metric matters here</h2>

    <p>
        Because only the elected delegates produce blocks, the leader distribution should be
        <em>even</em> across them — each delegate should propose roughly the same number of
        blocks per term. The simulator computes this with the <strong>Gini coefficient</strong>:
    </p>

    <ul>
        <li>Gini = 0 → perfectly even rotation (ideal)</li>
        <li>Gini = 1 → one delegate hogs everything (broken)</li>
    </ul>

    <p>
        A healthy DPoS simulation should show Gini close to zero. If it's high, either the
        scheduler is buggy or some delegates are silently dropping their slots.
    </p>

    <div class="try-it">
        <h3>🎮 Try it in the simulator</h3>
        <MudText Typo="Typo.body2" Class="mb-2">
            Run a DPoS simulation with 21 nodes (the classic EOS-style witness count) and a
            seed of your choice. Open the Specialized Analytics → DPoS tab and check the
            witness performance bar chart. Then check the Gini coefficient in the
            Performance Baselines page.
        </MudText>
        <MudButton Variant="Variant.Filled" Color="Color.Primary"
                   EndIcon="@Icons.Material.Filled.PlayCircle"
                   Href="/simulations">Run a DPoS simulation</MudButton>
        <MudButton Variant="Variant.Text" Color="Color.Primary"
                   EndIcon="@Icons.Material.Filled.QueryStats"
                   Href="/specialized-analytics">View DPoS analytics</MudButton>
    </div>

    <h2>Where next?</h2>
